05008nam a22006135i 9780822388593DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223885937 a10.1515/97808223885932doi  a(DE-B1597)551825  a(OCoLC)1224278646  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0450002bisacsh1 aWray, Matt, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNot Quite White :bWhite Trash and the Boundaries of Whiteness /cMatt Wray. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b18 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction White Trash as Social Difference: Groups, Boundaries, and Inequalities -- t1 Lubbers, Crackers, and PoorWhite Trash: Borders and Boundaries in the Colonies and the Early Republic -- t2 Imagining PoorWhites in the Antebellum South: Abolitionist and Pro-Slavery Fictions -- t3 ‘‘Three Generations of Imbeciles Are Enough’’: American Eugenics and PoorWhite Trash -- t4 ‘‘The Disease of Laziness’’: Crackers, PoorWhites, and Hookworm Crusaders in the New South -- t5 Limning the Boundaries of Whiteness -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhite trash. The phrase conjures up images of dirty rural folk who are poor, ignorant, violent, and incestuous. But where did this stigmatizing phrase come from? And why do these stereotypes persist? Matt Wray answers these and other questions by delving into the long history behind this term of abuse and others like it. Ranging from the early 1700s to the early 1900s, Not Quite White documents the origins and transformations of the multiple meanings projected onto poor rural whites in the United States. Wray draws on a wide variety of primary sources—literary texts, folklore, diaries and journals, medical and scientific articles, social scientific analyses—to construct a dense archive of changing collective representations of poor whites.Of crucial importance are the ideas about poor whites that circulated through early-twentieth-century public health campaigns, such as hookworm eradication and eugenic reforms. In these crusades, impoverished whites, particularly but not exclusively in the American South, were targeted for interventions by sanitarians who viewed them as “filthy, lazy crackers” in need of racial uplift and by eugenicists who viewed them as a “feebleminded menace” to the white race, threats that needed to be confined and involuntarily sterilized.Part historical inquiry and part sociological investigation, Not Quite White demonstrates the power of social categories and boundaries to shape social relationships and institutions, to invent groups where none exist, and to influence policies and legislation that end up harming the very people they aim to help. It illuminates not only the cultural significance and consequences of poor white stereotypes but also how dominant whites exploited and expanded these stereotypes to bolster and defend their own fragile claims to whiteness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDifference (Psychology). 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 0aRural poorzUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aSocial classeszUnited States. 0aSocial stratificationzUnited States. 0aStereotypes (Social psychology)zUnited States. 0aWhite peoplexRace identityzUnited States. 0aWhite peoplezUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aWhitesxRace identityzUnited States. 0aWhiteszUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Poverty & Homelessness.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107